‚Äâ So when I first started collecting fragrances I avoided anything with jasmine and tuberose and gardenia . . and heck even rose. . I stuck with mostly 'clean skin scent' fragrances or vanilla or fruity or spicy and woody. I think the most floral I got would have been purple florals like violet and Iris which I've always liked but to me they don't smell very floral. I could tolerate Jasmine in the background as long as it isn't prominent. But even with a Gourmand if there was a strong floral note in it I didn't like it. For example at first I didn't like Devotion because of the orange blossom. (Now I love it) But I really think with my sense of smell sometimes I get stuck in a certain scent profiles, and then when I depart from that I don't like it so I tried to experiment more with florals,  then one day I tried Nishane Hundred Silent Ways on a tester strip at the store, and I loved it and I ended up trying it on my skin and I loved it even more. . even though tuberose is the main floral in it which surprised me how much I liked it. Maybe just that day was the day I liked tuberose lol. I was sitting there thinking wait a sec I thought I don't like tuberose why is this so good. . Well it turns out that one fragrance after I bought a decant of it has made my sense of smell much more open to things with tuberose, and even Jasmine in them when the note is prominent since to me they have many similarities. I find myself enjoying a lot more fragrances now I'm not scared off if they are floral heavy. I still am not a big fan of sort of vintage aldehydes or indolic florals but there's so many good modern ones that I've been missing out. I admit though it's kind of hard to bounce from wearing vanilla Gourmand or fruity fragrances into wearing florals it feels like you need time to ...adjust almost? But I'm curious for anyone else have you ever done a complete "about face" on a certain note or family of notes because you loved a certain fragrance so much that had it, to where you know appreciated it more in other fragrances, like for me with Hundred Silent Ways ? The other one I am totally in love with is Printtemps Blanc which is super floral heavy. . and also lattafa atheeri. And Paris corner vanilla and roses.

Learn more about different kinds of eye drops and what they can do at Cleveland Clinic. ‚Äâ Perfumes are a nice hobby because how expensive it will be is entirely dependent on your choices in perfumes. Definitely not like watches, shoes, or something where it can become super expensive even for entry brands. Sometimes it depends on the brands of perfumes you buy. A lot of Middle Eastern brands, mainly Emirati, like Lattafa or Al Haramain usually create dupes/clones of the more expensive/mainstream fragrances that are pretty close to smelling like the real deal. It's not gonna be a hundred percent there obviously but they are still pretty good imo -- others in the perfume hobby may disagree with that though. Lattafa's fragrances, from my experience, can be bought for usually around 20-40 USD on sites like Fragrancenet. Also never buy perfumes from a retail store, Amazon etc. -- they up charge like hell. If you really want to experience the more expensive stuff you can always get smaller decants/samples of those fragrances for way cheaper. For example, a 3.4 oz bottle of Tom Ford is like 230 USD but you can get a 5 mL decant for like 25 bucks. Thats a quite extreme example because Tom Ford is ridiculously expensive but you get the idea. It's way more cost effective and 5 mL for me lasts like 4-5 months since I'm not using perfume every single day. Getting decants is also nice because you can sample way more perfumes without having to "commit" to certain fragrances.

‚Äâ After seeing a whole bunch of heavy handed "dos and don'ts" floating around, I decided to do one of my own. Why not, right? Not really a bunch of advice, just a few things I do and saves me a lot of headache, time, and stress. These are habits/culture I have picked up/developed over time. I have been there 300 years ago when Muglers were considered affordable high end and clones were thought of as knock offs, and then CDNIM became this underground resistance, and now we are here. Hopefully this helps some of you **Blind buying is viable only when:** You have done a good amount of research and are *very* familiar with the scent profiles/accords from other fragrances. That is to say if you like fig on frag1, doesn't mean you will like it in frag 2. But if you have liked it in frags 1-3, you will probably like it in 4, if the reviews (a lot of them) are saying it is good. There is still a chance you might not, but after these two criteria, that gets slim. **Decants are great for elevating your fragrance game:** A lot of people think of it as waste, but if you are new and haven't sampled 100s of frags, get decants. I have used fragrancenet for a long time, and I have always filled out one or two decants to get free shipping (most decants are between 2-8 CAD, more expensive, but not when it saved me 12$ of shipping). There might be good local sellers selling decants, and there are international shippers with some good reviews as well. Once you have reached that level, your blind buying success will go up if that's your thing. Or keep getting decants. You do you. **AIs are a great tool for research:** Right now its almost exclusively Gemini. If you know how to talk to AI efficiently (like its the monkey's paw which also needs a very clear and short statements) you can save yourself hours and hours of research as it can crawl the forums, assign points, give you a summary, ranking, whatever you want. If you want, I can show you some examples **Buying off of Amazon/eBay is safe if you know where to look:** Check the sellers, check how far back the reviews go, and generally how positive they are. If you don't want to put in the work, get a browser add on like Fakespot **If you are looking for specific profiles:** You can use Parfumo/Frgrantica. Parfumo can be curated way more - [here](https://www.parfumo.com/s_perfumes_x.php?v=grid&filter=&b_id=2163%2C17122%2C13458%2C385%2C2549%2C1135%2C351%2C189%2C582%2C8997%2C1808%2C8692%2C2819%2C8430%2C7397%2C10107%2C18424%2C2019%2C14885%2C8487%2C13722%2C16792%2C18829%2C17719&m_id=&pf_id=&c_id=&n_inc_id=&n_exc_id=&nc_inc_id=&nc_exc_id=&t_id=&o=nr_desc&filter=&g_m=1&g_f=1&g_u=1&y_t=2&y_0=&y_1=0&y_2=0&y_3=&n_t=1&cl_35=0&cl_26=0&cl_13=0&cl_14=0&cl_38=0&cl_15=0&cl_16=0&cl_17=0&cl_18=0&cl_27=0&cl_31=0&cl_19=0&cl_20=0&cl_21=0&cl_22=0&cl_36=0&cl_37=0&cl_34=0&cl_33=0&cl_23=0&cl_24=0&cl_9=0&cl_10=0&cl_11=0&cl_12=0&cl_25=0&cl_6=0&cl_7=0&cl_32=0&cl_8=0&cl_5=0&cl_4=0&cl_3=0&cl_1=0&cl_2=0) is a list of filters with the clone brands I have used (there might be more but if I haven't used them, I didnt add them to the filter), just look for the note group you want and take it from there. Once you get a result, google the frag's notes to make sure the notes in parfumo weren't wrong **"Nuclear" doesn't have to be a thing:** You are not likely to wear the same clothing for 10 hours+, so anything that pushes past 8-10 hours doesn't add that much value, at least to me. But anything that lasts longer, *likely* projects more as well, if its an EDP or the old school chemical warfare grade EDTs. Extraits are by design heavier to last longer, but with less alcohol, project less. Ideally, I want a few nuclears but I don't aim for most in my collection to be. **Always check multiple shops even if they are international:** Specially if you are buying multiple frags - chances are at the other retailer across the ocean is charging you twice for the shipping but their frags being cheaper will work out cheaper total order cost (for the sites that do duty paid shipping like Joma, Fragrancenet and FragranceX) **Don't discount smaller houses:** Armaf and Lattafa were once little known in NA. CDNIM used to cost 20$. There are new houses popping up (could be an old house previously not in the spotlight), relatively unknown but doing solid work. I recently got some Azhas for 20 CAD. These easily match most of my 30$ stuff. I'll review them in a week when they have matured - they are getting better every day. Not saying blind buy, just give them a chance. **Clone Perfumeries are your friend:** I make a distinction between mass production houses like Lattafa where they have a formula and mass producing them based on it. There's always going to be quality and batch variations. Smaller entities, like a perfumery that makes approximation is using the exact formula 1:1 they set as the recipe for a clone in every bottle. The quality will be higher on average. Cost is a different thing though....

‚Äâ Yesterday, I received my new perfume in the mail from Amazon - Sensuelle by Risala! This is the first ever Arabic fragrance I have added to my collection! I'm so excited to have more coming in the mail soon! I should be getting two arriving today and one on Monday. So far, I've bought this one, Yara, Haya & Rave Now, all three perfumes by the Arabic brand Lattafa. risala_perfumes_official Top Notes: Litchi, rhubarb, and tangerine. Middle Notes: Tropical fruits, peony, rose, and gourmand accord. Base Notes: Sandalwood, cashmeran, vanilla, and musk. First Impressions: The fragrance is a very girly & soft, fruity-floral sweet type of scent and the bottle is really pretty. It does project well, and I can easily smell myself with it on when I'm walking around outside in the sun. I've only worn it for a couple of hours, and it seemed to be holding up decently well. Update: After wearing for a few hours, it does fade away easily, so I recommend wearing it with a scented body lotion & body oil + Vaseline on pulse points to get it to last longer. It does, in fact, dry down to a more gourmand type of scent with the vanilla really shining through in the base. Also, it kind of smells like coconut with a really smooth velvety quality to it. So it might go great with some coconut scented body care products! (maybe Victoria's Secret Pink - Coco mist and lotion?) Honestly though, I was expecting a strawberry milkshake type of scent because of this one TikTok review that I watched where the girl said it smelled like that. Also, I didn't read the scent notes after to confirm if it had strawberry as an actual scent note or not, which is, of course, my own fault. I'd give it a 6.5/10 for the overall scent. I will be keeping it in my perfume collection and using it tonight as my bedtime scent! #risalasensuelle #risala #sensuelle #perfume #perfumebottle #perfumecollection #perfumelovers #perfumeaddict #perfumeaddicted #perfumeaddiction #arabic #arabicperfume #arabicfragrance #fragrance #fragrances #fragrancelover #fragrancecommunity #perfumereview #fragrancereviews #pink #pinkperfume #pinkaesthetic #pinkfragrance

‚Äâ Nora is 32 and her little sister is 29. They're estranged from their absent father, and their mother passed 12 years prior. Parent loss is always something that pulls at my heartstrings in books. The relationship Libby and Nora have as sisters is honestly very close and endearing. This really is a sister closeness relationship story with - 55% being about the sisters and 45% being about the romance with our man main character. I enjoy reading about sisters who are close, and these two have gone on a getaway trip to sunshine falls North Carolina where our other main character Charlie is from. Charlie and Nora have a bad business meeting over a book Nora asked Charlie to edit. Charlie is extremely rude in Nora's opinion about the book, but later finds out why he was so rude that day. As their relationship expands they turn from enemies, to lovers. This was the first book I've ever read to mention an actual fragrance. The fragrance is called book by commodity. They're both wearing the same one our two main characters, and it actually brings them together more. I love that so much! I have a fragrance collection, and the closest thing I have to the same notes as this is Liam by Lattafa. Both scents are woody, warm spicy, powdery, and green. Two book enthusiasts would wear a fragrance named book. Emily Henry mentions multiple different kinds of fragrances in the book, and how they bring up memories for the main character and that made me happy. ‚Äâ Four days ago, I received my new perfume in the mail from Amazon - Sensuelle by Risala! (Eau de Parfum). This is the first ever Arabic fragrance I have added to my collection! I'm so excited to have more coming in the mail soon! I should be getting two arriving today and one on Monday. So far, I've bought this one, Yara, Haya & Rave Now, all three perfumes by the Arabic brand Lattafa. risala_perfumes_official Top Notes: Litchi, rhubarb, and tangerine. Middle Notes: Tropical fruits, peony, rose, and gourmand accord. Base Notes: Sandalwood, cashmeran, vanilla, and musk. First Impressions: The fragrance is a very girly & soft, fruity-floral sweet type of scent and the bottle is really pretty. It does project well, and I can easily smell myself with it on when I'm walking around outside in the sun. I've only worn it for a couple of hours, and it seemed to be holding up decently well. Update: After wearing for a few hours, it does fade away easily, so I recommend wearing it with a scented body lotion & body oil + Vaseline on pulse points to get it to last longer. It does, in fact, dry down to a more gourmand type of scent with the vanilla really shining through in the base. Also, it kind of smells like coconut with a really smooth velvety quality to it. So it might go great with some coconut scented body care products! (maybe vspink - Coco mist and lotion?) Honestly though, I was expecting a strawberry milkshake type of scent because of this one TikTok review that I watched where the girl said it smelled like that. Also, I didn't read the scent notes after to confirm if it had strawberry as an actual scent note or not, which is, of course, my own fault. I'd give it a 7/10 for the overall scent. I do still enjoy this fragrance, and it will be a part of my everyday fragrance rotation. I give it a 7/10 for the overall scent. The staying power and projecting power is decent. I'd give it 3-5 hours before having to re-apply! I would probably combine this fragrance with the new victoriassecret - Bare Vanilla Bliss mist and lotion! ‚Äâ Oud is one of the most popular scents in the world, but for some perfume enthusiasts, its powerful presence can be intimidating. The Perfume Closet explains how to pick the right oud fragrance for you. (firmenpresse) - Sometimes called "liquid gold," oud been cherished for centuries in Middle Eastern fragrance traditions and is now experiencing a renaissance in Western perfumery. Yet for some fragrance enthusiasts, oud‚Äîwith its powerful presence and strong profile‚Äîcan be intimidating. How do you choose the right oud fragrance that suits your personality and lifestyle? Interested in learning more about Arabian perfumes? You can find all the information you need at The Perfume Closet UK https://www.theperfumecloset.co.uk/product-category/brands/arabian-fragrances/ Understanding the Complexity of OudUnlike most perfume ingredients harvested from flowers, fruits, or spices, oud involves a more complex process. A resin, oud forms only when the Aquilaria tree becomes infected with a particular fungus, or when it's injured or infested by insects. The tree's defense mechanism produces a rich, resinous heartwood that, when distilled, yields one of perfumery's most precious ingredients. This origin story explains why genuine oud commands such extraordinary prices. Oud can cost around $5,000 per pound, a price point that has historically kept oud fragrances in the realm of luxury collections. Today, however, more accessible interpretations are emerging. The Oud Spectrum: Finding Your MatchWhat many fragrance newcomers don't realize is that oud isn't a single scent profile but rather a spectrum of aromatic possibilities. Traditional¬†Deep Woods - At one end of the spectrum lies traditional oud with its profound depth. These fragrances showcase oud's natural characteristics: woody, slightly animalic, with subtle hints of leather and earth. They're uncompromising and authentic, best suited for those who appreciate heritage and want to experience oud in its most traditional form. Sweet Amber - Moving along, we encounter oud blended with amber and balsamic notes. These combinations soften oud's intensity while preserving its distinctive character, creating a warmer, more approachable profile that works beautifully in cooler weather. Smoke and Incense - Another traditional interpretation pairs oud with incense notes like frankincense and myrrh. These compositions suit evening wear and moments when you want something profound but not overwhelming. Contemporary¬†Bright Citrus - Modern perfumers have discovered that pairing oud with bright citrus notes creates an unexpected but beautiful contrast. These blends juxtapose oud's depth against the sparkle of bergamot, lemon, or mandarin, making them perfect daytime options for oud enthusiasts. Gourmand Fusion - Another innovative direction blends oud with gourmand elements like vanilla, tonka bean, or even chocolate. These creations feel indulgent and comforting‚Äîideal for those who appreciate sweetness but want something with more sophistication than typical dessert-inspired scents. Green Interpretation - Perhaps the most unexpected modern take introduces green notes alongside oud. Fresh herbs, violet leaf, or fig can transform oud into something surprisingly refreshing and versatile for everyday wear. Tips for Selecting Oud FragrancesDon't Rush the Decision - Unlike lighter fragrances that reveal themselves immediately, oud perfumes evolve significantly over time. What might seem overwhelming at first spray often settles into something much more nuanced after 30 minutes. A full day's wear may help you better judge an oud fragrance. Test on Your Skin: Oud interacts dramatically with individual skin chemistry. What smells divine on your friend might present completely differently on you. Factor in Seasonality - Heavier oud compositions that feel perfect in December might become cloying in July. Consider having different oud options for different seasons, or focus on lighter interpretations if you live in warmer climates. Overlooking Concentration - The concentration matters enormously with oud. An eau de toilette will present oud's character very differently than a parfum or attar. Higher concentrations aren't necessarily "better"‚Äîthey're simply different experiences. Finding Quality Without Breaking the BankWhile pure oud commands astronomical prices, quality oud fragrances don't have to empty your bank account. The key is understanding what you're paying for: Synthetic vs. Natural - Many excellent contemporary oud fragrances use high-quality synthetic oud accords that effectively replicate natural oud without the extreme price tag. These aren't "fake" but rather skilled interpretations that can be remarkably beautiful. Concentration and Longevity - A modestly priced oud fragrance with excellent longevity often represents better value than a more expensive option that fades quickly. UK retailers like The Perfume Closet understand this balance, offering options like their Luminous Oud that provides impressive longevity at accessible price points. The Blending Factor - Well-crafted blends where oud plays a supporting rather than starring role can offer exceptional value. These fragrances capture oud's magic without requiring massive quantities of raw material that drive up prices. Finding Your Oud Journey PartnerFinding a retailer that understands oud's complexities can transform your exploration from overwhelming to enjoyable. The Perfume Closet in Birmingham has built its reputation on guiding customers through the oud landscape with expertise and patience. With their expanded Arabian perfume collection featuring over 600 fragrances‚Äîincluding renowned houses like Lattafa and Ajmal alongside their own Luminous Oud creation‚Äîthey exemplify the kind of knowledgeable guidance that makes oud accessible to newcomers and connoisseurs alike. "We believe everyone should have the chance to discover their perfect oud fragrance," notes Saj, the founder. "That's why we offer options across price points and encourage customers to take their time testing before committing."...

‚Äâ Hey everyone! Just wanted to take a moment to thank this amazing community, you've all helped me so much over the past few months. The passion, knowledge, and honest feedback here really guided me through my fragrance journey. In the last 4 months, I went all in tried over 150+ decants, visited a few local perfumeries, and explored and owned tons of perfume oils beyond what I'm sharing in this post. After a lot of research (and a bit of obsession), I ended up collecting these fragrances, and let's just say‚Ä¶ it became quite the addiction! That said, I've decided to hit pause and not buy any more fragrances for the rest of the year (with one exception that might arrive in the next couple of days). I'll still be around and happy to help anyone here however I can. Thanks again for being such a great part of this journey! **Note**: I am not an expert , I trust my nose more than reviews, please do research or test fragrances before you buy, I am from Middle east / Asia English is not my native language, I apologize in advance for any mistakes i try to explain this in my words without using any AI or correction tool. I am reviewing all fragrances after giving them time to mature. From Top Left to Right: 1. **Icon by Dunhill**: Really Good citrusy, Aromatic and floral scent. A good alternative for those who don't like sweet or overly citrusy scents for summer. 2. **1 Million Prive:** The most complimented one on my list, absolutely amazing winter scent with sweet and tobacco notes; I failed to find anything that can beat that fragrance. 3. **1 Million Elixir:** Very sweet and creamy vanilla with colorful floral tones, especially on the dry down. Lasts a long time and projection is strong. **4. ** ¬† **Jasoor:** Clone of VUBIR Coral Fantasy Long Lasting with Good projection, Very Versatile for year-round wear except very hot evenings. **5. ** ¬† **Asad Bourbon:** Clone that covers VUBIR Intense, Most Wanted and Stronger with you. Smells cozy and rich. Feels confident and warm. **6. ** ¬† **Khamrah :** Amazing Scent, Sweet,¬† Warm , Cozy with Vanilla and amber. 7. **Khamrah Dukhan:** I tried Liquid Burn, and to my nose, it smells quite similar that same warm, spicy DNA. But Khamrah Dukhan was much cheaper, so I went for it. It's incredibly long-lasting and feels like a spicier, less sweet version of Khamrah.
